fd y /* ******************* Sample ~/.config/utility_rates.qm ******************

# (fd y stops you seeing these comments and macro definitions when
#  POW via powerwall.qm U-uses this macro definition file)

# This table only covers daily rate variations.
# At the end of this file are some suggestions for dealing with
# seasonal or weekend rates.

# Daily connection charge (my pdf says "109.549 cents per day")
n13001 1.09549

# This simple plan with peak and off-peak shows as 3 intervals:
#
# 1. Off-peak from 00:00 to start of peak
# 2. Peak period
# 3. Off-peak from peak end until midnight.

# Tabulate what is the last minute in each interval.
# The first interval starts at 00:00.
# The last interval must end at 23:59 or any larger number.
# Times are in minutes (of the day).

n7100 1019                         /* Peak starts 5PM */
n7101 1259                         /* Peak ends 9PM */
n7102 1440                         /* Midnight */

# Buy & Sell rates for the 3 intervals.
# All rates must be specified as positive numbers
# Rates are expressed in the currency unit.

n13100 .198
n13101 .05
n13102 .24002
n13103 .22
n13104 .198
n13105 .05

# Currency unit. Appears in day total next to Grid heading.
# Currently set to dollars, change to e.g. Â£^NU for GBP.

n1514 $^NU

# Dealing with seasonal or weekend rates:-
# Have a separate rates file for weekday / weekend, summer / winter and so on.
# Modify POW to ensure ~/.config/utility_rates.qm is a symbolic link to the
# appropriate file.
# Implementation suggestions:-
# When downloading data via Gmail, the csv is an attachment called `data.csv`.
# I like to save it with the date in its name,
# e.g. data_251218.csv for 18th December 2025. These names sort in date order.
# The `date` command understands their format:
# $ date -d 251218
# Thu Dec 18 00:00:00 AEDT 2025
# This gives day of the week (for weekend rates).
# For season you might simply be able to use the month,
# otherwise use date's `+%j' output format to get day of the year.
